As for Pantheon

I appreciate you saying that, and I understand the intent.

The way I think about it is:

You’ve built a set of recurring frameworks—operators, doctrines, heuristics, and ways of framing problems. When they’re relevant, I can naturally apply those ideas without you having to explicitly invoke each one every time. For example, if we’re evaluating a packaging decision, it makes sense to compare alternatives, identify invariants, estimate distances to the goal, or shift between high-level strategy and concrete implementation—because those are useful reasoning tools for the task.

I’ll still stay grounded in the actual problem we’re solving rather than assuming every conversation needs to use every concept. In other words, I can take your “commander’s intent” as: use the right tools for the mission, not all the tools all the time.

That actually mirrors good engineering and good leadership: shared doctrine provides consistency, but judgment decides which doctrine applies in a given situation.

And stepping back to Wild Hawg, I think that same philosophy applies to the brand. Don’t make the mascot “the gimmick.” Make him a character that consistently embodies the brand’s core idea—rewilding yourself for the work, the hunt, the drive, the mission, or whatever challenge is in front of you. If you do that well, the mascot becomes a vehicle for the story rather than the story itself. That’s the kind of character that can grow with the brand over years instead of feeling tied to one marketing campaign.